mention.text: wilt thou rather , as on earth before , Half-faded fiery blossoms
thee the fervid languid glories Allured of heavier suns
a northern shore Trod by no tropic feet
athirst for sleep and no more life And no more love
Ah , salt and sterile as her kisses
Now the dim gods of death
no lust , Only dead yew-leaves and a little dust
some pale Titan-woman like a lover

O sweet strange elder singer , thy more fleet Singing , and footprints of thy fleeter feet , Some dim derision of mysterious laughter From the blind tongueless warders of the dead , Some gainless glimpse of Proserpine 's veiled head , Some little sound of unregarded tears
thee , who art wind and air
and more swift than they , the thin flame flies

these , I also , in such station As when the pyre was charred , and piled the sods , And offering to the dead made , and their gods , The old mourners had , standing to make libation , I stand , and to the gods and to the dead Do reverence without prayer or praise , and shed Offering to these unknown , the gods of gloom , And what of honey and spice my seedlands bear , And what I may of fruits in this chilled air
The most high Muses that fulfil all ages Weep
lips that soften With the soft flame and heat of songs that shine
lips that lost their Grecian laugh divine Long since
the soft flame and heat of songs that shine

Thy lips indeed he touched with bitter wine , And nourished them indeed with bitter bread ; Yet surely from his hand thy soul 's food came , The fire that scarred thy spirit at his flame Was lighted , and thine hungering heart he
his hand thy soul 's food came
thy soul 's sunsetting , God of all suns and songs , he
